status_message:
A year ago I wrote that Trump didn't really want to win, that his campaign was merely a grotesque exercise in marketing. Then I began to doubt that. Gradually, I accepted that Trump was serious, that this was really happening. But now I'm not so sure. Maybe Trump has just hit the wall and realizes it's over. Maybe this is what he wanted all along. It doesn't matter in either case. This is pure self-sabotage.

Trump is laying the groundwork for his defeat, and cementing the narrative that he was ambushed by the establishment, by the Republican Party. He will lose, and he will tell his army of illiterates that the crown was stolen from him. They'll believe him, too, because this is a cult of personality, and cults are for the credulous.

But let's not get bogged down in the details. The good news is that Trump is combusting in slow motion, and that's a beautiful thing. I still fear what follows his calamitous campaign, but it's essential that he lose in November, and that appears more likely every day.
link_name: Unshackled Trump declares war on GOP

status_message:
"If this storm had a name or if it happened in a city the country recognizes, anchors and camera crews would abound. Instead, it's a half-reported B-story. The disaster porn coverage the networks liberally apply to non-stories all the damn time isn't coming. But this is a sprawling human tragedy, and it's happening right now, just beyond the view of a media more interested in Justin Bieber's Instagram status than in the sufferings of flyover country.

I lived in Louisiana nearly half of my life. I know the people there. They're a strong, spirited lot. They have a way of singing and dancing around pain. They'll close ranks and deal with the challenges ahead. But more people should know about their struggle. That so many don't is itself a tragedy, and the national media is largely to blame. They appear to be coming around to the horrors they neglected, a good thing to be sure, but shame on them for taking so long."
link_name: Louisiana's quiet crisis: Cable news and the folly of disaster porn coverage
